{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes—unit-testing only the sort function can miss failures in file discovery + execution wiring. REAL-INFRA: no OS/subprocess beyond normal local FS/DB use. MOCK-HIDE: yes—mocked executor may not reveal wrong execution order against real metadata updates. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Run the migration runner against a disposable PostgreSQL database with a real `migrations/` directory containing out-of-order filenames (e.g., `010_b.sql`, `002_a.sql`, `020_c.sql`) where each script inserts its version into an `applied_order` table. Assert final rows show execution in numeric-prefix ascending order (`002`, `010`, `020`).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes—idempotency depends on persisted DB state across runs. REAL-INFRA: no external network/service required beyond local DB/filesystem. MOCK-HIDE: yes—mocked `_migrations` reads/writes can hide duplicate-apply bugs. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Using a disposable PostgreSQL database, run the runner twice on the same migration set where one migration has a visible side effect (e.g., insert with unique key). After run 1, verify `_migrations` has one record per file. After run 2, verify no new side effects occurred and `_migrations` row count is unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes—rollback/transaction semantics are DB behavior, not just app logic. REAL-INFRA: local DB transaction behavior is sufficient; no extra system boundary needed. MOCK-HIDE: yes—mock transaction clients often always succeed and can hide partial-commit bugs. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Create three migrations: (1) valid change, (2) migration with one successful statement then a failing statement, (3) valid change that should never run. Execute runner once against disposable PostgreSQL. Assert migration (2) left no partial effects, migration (3) was not applied, and `_migrations` records only completed migrations before the failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes—true race conditions appear across process boundaries. REAL-INFRA: yes—requires concurrent subprocesses and real DB locking/constraints under contention. MOCK-HIDE: yes—in-process mocks or single-process tests can serialize behavior and miss duplicate-apply races. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Spawn two separate runner processes simultaneously (barrier-synchronized start) pointing to the same disposable PostgreSQL database and same migration directory. Use migrations with observable side effects and unique constraints. Wait for both to finish; assert each migration’s side effect appears exactly once and `_migrations` has exactly one row per migration version.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: yes—ordering between bootstrap metadata creation and first migration execution is wiring + DB state dependent. REAL-INFRA: no subprocess/network beyond local DB/filesystem. MOCK-HIDE: yes—mock metadata layer can bypass real creation-order failures. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no.","test_description":"Against a fresh disposable PostgreSQL database with no `_migrations` table, run the runner with a first migration that is guaranteed to execute only after metadata setup (e.g., verify runner can record its own version in `_migrations`). Assert `_migrations` exists after startup and that first migration succeeded with a recorded metadata row.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
